ASAPP Data Science Interview¶


by Jakub Langr

Executive Summary¶

  • Machine Learning shows notable potential in this application (~$15k) for the 500 loans evaluated (see later slides for explanation of this value
  • Significant investments into data quality and data warehouses would payoffespecially if more applications are to be deployed
  • There are many more directions data science can take this datasetfrom traditional business analytics to GDPR compliancebut they would require more contextual knowledge
  • Part of the value of this exercise are the data quality issues we have documented (see appendix)

Explaining fundamentals¶

The presentation will first explain the Business value and then provide the technical detail, in the following areas.

We followed a simple process to get to where we are currently:

  1. We loaded the raw data into memory and visualized data
  2. We merged and cleaned the data to provide early insights
  3. We ran a dummy classifier and a Machine Learning Classifier to test performance
  4. We tuned the classifier and compared it with another state of the art classifier.
  5. We provide further data insights and propose future directions

Business value¶

  • We were provided with a dataset of 515 loans to classify.
  • The first potentially valuable use-case is to automate the work of the loan workers
  • Initial hypothesis is that we can mirror loan officer choices sufficiently enough of the the time to do about as well as humans
  • Potential savings: # num loan cases x # hours spent per case x # hourly loan officer pay (NB: fully loaded cost to the business, not hourly salary)
  • Assumed business value: 515 * 1 * 30 = $15,450
  • Please note that our ML algorithm mayin actual factbe doing much better (or much worse) than real officers, because we do not see the default rates, but just decisions that humans have made

Technical Slides¶

We have loaded the cases into memory and merged the four different data sources together.

There were a number of issues:

  1. All TSVs did not follow the standard convention for Tab Separated Values to be separated by \t
  2. Headers inconsistent and/or missing
  3. Delete one row in borrower: - Emp Mvd Age Home CurEmp Dep
  4. Num rows in result (seemingly copy-paste from SQL)
  5. Interpreting 1 in results as Y
  6. result is duplicated (2x)all values appear 2x

Data Understanding (2/2)¶

Machine Learning (1/3)¶

  • Good experimental design required a split into Train and Test sets.
  • This unfortunately meant that both were even smaller
  • We know that machine learning is possible, so we first want to compare it with a very naive strategy DummyClassifer
  • We then took a state of the art RandomForrestClassifier and ran a hyperparameter search to get a score of:
  • Here is a quick explanation of what RandomForest does:

Machine Learning (2/3)¶

  • DummyClassifier accurracy of 68.2% and ROC AUC score of .5
  • RandomForestClassifer Accuracy: 75% and ROC AUC score of .64
  • XGboostClassifer ROC AUC: .60 (XGboost is typically considered a state of the art)

Machine Learning (3/3)¶

Next steps:

  • More data
  • More extensive hyper parameter search (We tried a few set-ups)
  • More feature engineering
  • More classifiers / Ensambles
  • Synthetic data?
  • Better understanding of errors

Further insights and research directions (1/4)¶

We can provide some explanations, if required. Typically GDPR of other financial decisions need to be explained. Even if not, may be better for management understanding.

  • First of all, we will showcase 'Shap' values as a way to understand why a particular decision has been done on a single case
  • Subsequently, we will explore what this means in all the cases.
  • This understanding can also give us a sense check against business logic and requirements.
  • Last, but not least, this kind of diagnostics can tell us whether these are the kinds of trade-offs we're happy with.

Further insights and research directions (2/4)¶

In [22]:
import shap, pickle
import pandas as pd
rand_search = pickle.load(open('rand_search.p','rb'))
X_train = pd.read_csv('X_train.csv')
shap.initjs()

explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(rand_search.best_estimator_)
example = X_train.iloc[0,]
shap_values = explainer.shap_values(example)
shap.force_plot(explainer.expected_value[0], shap_values[0], example)

Further insights and research directions (4/4)¶

If you are happy with the:

  1. business case
  2. evidence of efficacy
  3. lack of bias so far

We can talk about the next practical steps in deploymentimpact on the day-to-day operations. Here we see the class distribution (predicted by the model). Remember that the business would need to honor this distribution of loans. Is that something that is acceptable?

Conclusion¶

  • The aim of this presentation is to demonstrate potential of machine learning, not the specifics.
  • There is up to $15k of upside for this project alone and it will only scale linearly with the number of cases (e.g. at 100k cases processed the revenue is $3M)
  • It is difficult to assess whether the project would be an overall net-benefit to the organization, because it is unclear from the data alone how effective are the loan officers.
  • Investments in Data Quality would allow for more applications

Thank you.

Appendix¶

There are already noticeable investments in infrastructure requirements.

  • All of the data quality issues noticed on the Technical slide are an issue.
  • Data warehousing and consistent data store (e.g. postgres) would be very helpful for data scientists plugging directly into the data.
  • Column names already in the data store would be very helpful and having more context joined with the data names would be extremely helpful for further data analysis.
  • Further data warehousing, data quality and data management advice is available upon request.
